    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>March 22. 76</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for your kind letter. I am always glad to hear of the spreading of the principles of Evolution, and all who battle in the cause do good service, as I believe, for the progress of Science.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I cannot think of any particular points in the Nat: History of Bermuda about which I want information but I am much obliged for your kind offer of assistance.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I have no doubt that you will find many subjects in this Island &amp; in the W. Indies, well worthy of investigation, &amp; with my best hopes for your success I remain | Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">To | Ernest de Hesse Wartegg Esq. | Philadei.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Hesse-Wartegg’s letter has not been found. He had previously written to CD about a review of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref> ([Hesse-Wartegg] 1875b) and an article about CD’s life (Hesse-Wartegg 1875a); see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 23, letters from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2265.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ernst von Hesse-Wartegg</ref>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10123.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">16 August 1875</ref> and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10162.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">20 September 1875</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Hesse-Wartegg travelled extensively in North America, India, and East Asia, and wrote a series of travel books (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5928.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">OBL</hi></ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
